Ricker models for harrison data

Ricker simple

Simple Ricker model of the form: \(R_{t} = a*S_{t}*exp(-b*S_{t}) *exp(\epsilon_{t})\)

\(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma)\)

parameters MLE median low high
a 3.5816170 3.1968760 1.8650990 6.1678020
b 0.0000067 0.0000056 0.0000016 0.0000112
\(\sigma\) 0.7968511 0.8351971 0.6566749 1.1162977

Figure 1. Posterior probability distributions for simple Ricker model.

Ricker with autocorrelation

Ricker model with autocorrelation in residuals of the form:

\(R_t = a*S_t*exp(-b*S_t) *exp(\epsilon_t +\epsilon_{t-1} *\rho)\)

\(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma_{AR})\)

\(\sigma_{AR} = \sigma * sqrt(1-\rho^2)\)

parameters MLE median low high
a 2.9891348 2.3925715 1.4001706 4.9580074
b 0.0000050 0.0000025 0.0000002 0.0000091
\(\sigma_{AR}\) 0.7743725 0.8265325 0.6456326 1.1047622
\(\rho\) 0.2182485 0.2857355 -0.0507976 0.5544011

Figure . Posterior probability distributions for Ricker model with autocorrelation.

Ricker with time-varying productivity

Ricker model with time-varying productivity

\(R_t = a_t*S_t*exp(-b*S_t) *exp(\epsilon_t )\)

\(a_t = a_{t-1} + v_t\)

\(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma)\)

\(v \sim N(0,\sigma_{a})\)

\(\sigma_{tot}= sqrt(\sigma^2 + \sigma_{a}^2)\)

Parameter estimates for model with time-varying productivity.

Ricker model with survival as covariate

In this model we use survival as part of the model. In this version, the classic productivity parameter is replaced by \(a*surv_t\)

\(R_t = a*surv_t*S_t*exp(-b*S_t) *exp(\epsilon)\)

\(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma)\)

Figure. Survival to age two estimates.

Figure. Posterior probability distributions for Ricker with survival as a covariate.

Ricker model with survival and fecundity as covariates

In this version of the model we describe the ricker productivity as function of two covariates. the survival index and a fecundity index. We use z-scores for these covariates.

\(R_t = a_t*S_t*exp(-b*S_t) *exp(\epsilon)\)

\(a_t = a_0+ \gamma_1*surv_t \gamma_2 * fec_t\)

\(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma)\)

Figure. z-scores for fecundity and survival covariates

Figure. Posterior probability distributions for Ricker with survival as a covariate.
